org.jmisb.api.common

Class InvalidDataHandler

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jmisb.api.common.InvalidDataHandler

  • public class InvalidDataHandler
extends Object
    Handler for invalid data cases.

    This is a singleton implementation that allows different strategies to be applied to different kinds of invalid data.

      • handleInvalidChecksum

        public void handleInvalidChecksum(org.slf4j.Logger logger,
                                  String message)
                           throws KlvParseException
        Handle the case where the checksum is invalid.

        Invalid in this case means that the checksum is present, but does not have the expected value. This usually indicates some kind of data corruption in the message between production and processing. It could mean that the producer has an incorrect checksum implementation. Its possible that it indicates an error in the jMISB implementation.

        Parameters:
        logger - source logger, not null
        message - a message associated with the source event, ideally describing the nature of the invalid data
        Throws:
        KlvParseException - if the handling strategy chooses to throw.

      • handleMissingChecksum

        public void handleMissingChecksum(org.slf4j.Logger logger,
                                  String message)
                           throws KlvParseException
        Handle the case where the checksum is missing.

        Missing in this case means that the checksum is required, but is not present. This usually means an incorrect producer implementation.

        Do not use this in cases where the checksum is optional.

        Parameters:
        logger - source logger, not null
        message - a message associated with the source event, ideally describing the nature of the invalid data
        Throws:
        KlvParseException - if the handling strategy chooses to throw.

      • handleOverrun

        public void handleOverrun(org.slf4j.Logger logger,
                          String message)
                   throws KlvParseException
        Handle the case where the the parsing overruns the available data.

        Overrun means that not enough data was available to complete the current parse option. In KLV parsing, this could mean some the available length is less than the length specified by the L part of the KLV. This usually results from some kind of data corruption, or incorrect producer implementation.

        Parameters:
        logger - source logger, not null
        message - a message associated with the source event, ideally describing the nature of the invalid data
        Throws:
        KlvParseException - if the handling strategy chooses to throw.
